The precious stones of the costlier sort most in use by Roman women were pearls (margaritae) and eme- ralds (smaragdi). They were chiefly worn in necklaces, and as ear-drops and rings; and libertinae distinguished for their beauty could make a great display of jewels received as presents from their admirere.

annals (as Acron says), and there any one may find them, but she cannot get them back.
